					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Yes and if it's a one player game you read bit 0 and bit 1 of $4016 as controller 1 data so that either standard or expansion controller can be used. If it's a two player game you also read bit 0 and bit 1 of $4017 as controller 2 data. This is what (most) commercial games do.<br />Only if you have a three or four player game you would treat bit 0 of $4016 and $4017 as separate data (as controller 1 and 2) from bit 1 (as controller 3 and 4). In that case you would also want to support the four score.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">IMAGICA wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I need to learn buffering first</div><br />The Nerdy Nights sound tutorial actually has a (graphic) buffering system that is worth studying.</div>

